{:proof/updated-at "2026-03-29T20:33:34.413657068Z", :proof/falsify-completed? true, :proof/cycles [{:cycle/id "apm-a01A03-C001", :cycle/blocker-id "root", :cycle/phase :completed, :cycle/phases-completed [:observe :propose :execute :validate :classify :integrate :commit :gate-review], :cycle/phase-data {:observe {:blocker-id "root", :notes "g * f' = f(x+h) - f(x-h) for all f in C^1(R). Show g = chi_{[-h,h]}. The identity must hold for ALL C^1 functions, so we can identify g via Fourier analysis."}, :propose {:approach "Take Fourier transforms. LHS: ghat(xi) * (2*pi*i*xi) * fhat(xi). RHS: fhat(xi) * (e^{2*pi*i*h*xi} - e^{-2*pi*i*h*xi}) = 2i*sin(2*pi*h*xi)*fhat(xi). Since this holds for all f in C^1, ghat(xi) = sin(2*pi*h*xi)/(pi*xi) = FT(chi_{[-h,h]}). So g = chi_{[-h,h]} a.e.", :notes "The Fourier transform approach is clean and direct. The key computation: FT(chi_{[-h,h]})(xi) = int_{-h}^h e^{-2*pi*i*xi*t} dt = sin(2*pi*h*xi)/(pi*xi)."}, :execute {:artifacts ["proof-inline"], :notes "PROOF: Take Fourier transforms of both sides. LHS: FT(g * f') = ghat * FT(f') = ghat(xi) * 2*pi*i*xi * fhat(xi). RHS: FT(f(x+h) - f(x-h)) = fhat(xi) * e^{2*pi*i*h*xi} - fhat(xi) * e^{-2*pi*i*h*xi} = 2i*sin(2*pi*h*xi)*fhat(xi). Equating: ghat(xi) * 2*pi*i*xi = 2i*sin(2*pi*h*xi) for all xi (since fhat is arbitrary among transforms of C^1 functions). For xi != 0: ghat(xi) = sin(2*pi*h*xi)/(pi*xi). This is exactly the Fourier transform of chi_{[-h,h]}: FT(chi_{[-h,h]})(xi) = int_{-h}^h e^{-2*pi*i*xi*t} dt = (e^{-2*pi*i*xi*(-h)} - e^{-2*pi*i*xi*h})/(2*pi*i*xi) = 2*sin(2*pi*h*xi)/(2*pi*xi) = sin(2*pi*h*xi)/(pi*xi). Since ghat = FT(chi_{[-h,h]}), by uniqueness of Fourier transforms: g = chi_{[-h,h]} a.e. QED."}, :validate {:validation-artifacts ["informal-proof-complete"], :notes "Proof complete. Uses: convolution theorem, FT of derivative, FT of indicator. The condition 'for all f in C^1' is essential to determine ghat uniquely."}, :classify {:classification :proved, :rationale "Complete Fourier-analytic proof."}, :integrate {:rationale "Connects to distribution theory, fundamental theorem of calculus as a convolution identity, and the general principle that convolution identities are algebraic in Fourier space.", :ledger-changes []}, :commit {:saved? true}, :gate-review {:gates-passed true, :result-status :proved}}, :cycle/started-at "2026-03-29T20:34:59.940753902Z", :cycle/updated-at "2026-03-29T20:34:59.941354435Z", :cycle/result-status :proved}], :proof/ledger {"root" {:item/id "root", :item/label "Prove a01A03", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{}, :item/unlocks #{}, :item/evidence-type :analytical}}, :proof/active-license nil, :proof/current-mode :CONSTRUCT, :proof/problem-id "apm-a01A03", :proof/canonical {:statement "For $g\\in L^1(\\R)$ and any $f\\in C^1(\\R)$ suppose that $g \\ast\nf'(x)=f(x+h)-f(x-h)$. Show that $g \\equiv \\chi_{[-h,h]}$.\n", :closure-criterion "All parts proved analytically", :statement-hash "e8498d5265a94789e4ff73455174eb11f1b5e4a0ad97c15205458b605416c014", :version-history [{:version 0, :statement "For $g\\in L^1(\\R)$ and any $f\\in C^1(\\R)$ suppose that $g \\ast\nf'(x)=f(x+h)-f(x-h)$. Show that $g \\equiv \\chi_{[-h,h]}$.\n", :hash "e8498d5265a94789e4ff73455174eb11f1b5e4a0ad97c15205458b605416c014", :changed-at "2026-03-29T20:33:34.413657068Z", :reason "Initial load from APM archive"}]}, :proof/version 0, :proof/tryharder-log [], :proof/failed-routes []}